McDonald’s has made several changes to its leadership team, appointing Skye Anderson as chief operating officer of the domestic system, while Mason Smoot moves into the senior vice president of global franchising and delivery role.&nbsp;

The changes were shared in a note posted to McDonald’s website from McDonald’s USA president Joe Erlinger, chief financial officer Ian Borden, and global chief restaurant experience officer Jill McDonald. They said the leadership updates build on the company’s momentum and ensures it has the right leaders in place to “drive growth, execution, and enterprise transformation across the&nbsp;McDonald's System.”

Anderson has been with McDonald’s for more than 26 years, most recently serving as president of its Global Business Services organization, launched in 2023 to bring together shared services, finance transformation, people experience and transformation, human resources operations, and digital engagement teams. In that role, she oversaw the opening of McDonald’s GBS offices in Hyderabad, India, and Mexico City.&nbsp;

“Under her leadership, GBS has helped reimagine how we&nbsp;operate&nbsp;as a company — modernizing ways of working and building capabilities rooted in speed and agility so we can drive solutions into the business more effectively,” Erlinger, Borden, and McDonald wrote.&nbsp;

Prior to leading GBS, she was the U.S. West Zone president, and from 2017 to 2020, she served as field vice president of McDonald’s USA.&nbsp;

In the newly created COO role, Anderson will lead U.S. National Operations, Restaurant Development, and McOpCo (company-operated locations). She will also have oversight of the U.S. Supply Chain and U.S. Technology divisions to form an integrated operations team.

“Skye’s new role allows&nbsp;McDonald's USA&nbsp;to ensure that the systems,&nbsp;tools,&nbsp;and supply needed to deliver consistently strong restaurant experiences are aligned from end to end,” Erlinger, Borden, and McDonald wrote.&nbsp;

Smoot is a 30-year McDonald’s veteran who most recently served as chief restaurant officer of the U.S. system, a position he’s held since 2020. On his watch, the U.S. system has expanded through new and next-generation franchisees, experienced growth in the U.S. delivery business, and delivered improvements across operational metrics, including record-high customer satisfaction scores.

In his new role, Smoot will oversee global franchising standards, systemwide franchisee engagement, and enterprise frameworks to drive consistency across markets.&nbsp;

