Prior to his CRO role, Smoot held a variety of field and enterprise experience in operations, franchising, and human resources, including a seven-year stint as senior vice president of strategic alignment and chief of staff in the office of the CEO.&nbsp;

Finally, with Anderson’s move to the U.S. business Mattijs&nbsp;Backx&nbsp;has been promoted to chief transformation & services officer,&nbsp;joining&nbsp;the global senior leadership team. In this role, he will&nbsp;be responsible for&nbsp;leading GBS with a focus on simplifying ways of working, improving service delivery, and ensuring the right capabilities are in place to support growth across markets.

Backx joined McDonald’s two years ago as senior vice president of GBS Transformation. He has more than 25 years of experience in leadership positions at global companies such as PepsiCo, Lufthansa, and Office Depot.

These leadership changes come less than a week after the company promoted Tabassum Zalotrawala to senior vice president, global restaurant development and design.&nbsp;Zalotrawala, who joined the company in 2023 as U.S. chief development officer, has helped lead McDonald’s USA through its fastest development period in history. The chain is targeting 1,000 new domestic restaurants by 2027.&nbsp;

In September, McDonald’s added two new executives to its global impact team, including Kathy Baird, who took over as chief impact officer for McDonald’s USA, and Anne Hammer, who was named vice president and global chief communications officer. Also, last June, McDonald’s swapped roles for Whitney McGinnis and Valerie Ashbaugh to broaden their experience. With the change, McGinnis became senior vice president, commercial products and platforms, while Ashbaugh was named chief information officer and senior vice president, McDonald’s USA.

